Overview.Summary: The 2016 Croatian parliamentary election was held on September 11, and was the second election in ten months due to political uncertainty (2). The election was declared by President Kolinda Grabar-Kitarovic on July 30 (8,18). The election used the Mixed Member Proportional (MMP) voting system (16). The decision to hold early elections was made after the Audit of the Croatian National Bank (HNB) was proposed in Parliament (8). The election also saw Croatia Airlines welcome its one millionth passenger in 2016 (9). The election was held amid a deep division in Croatian football, as shown by an incident at Euro 2016 (19). The election resulted in a win for the Croatian Democratic Union (HDZ) party, with Božo Petrov elected as Speaker of Parliament (14).
